  "tutorial/response-status-code::section-0002": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/response-status-code::section-0002",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/response-status-code::section-0001",
    "level": 2,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "About HTTP status codes",
    "anchor_id": "about-http-status-codes",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/response-status-code/#about-http-status-codes",
    "section_text": "In HTTP, you send a numeric status code of 3 digits as part of the response.\n\nThese status codes have a name associated to recognize them, but the important part is the number.\n\nIn short:\n\n- 100 - 199 are for \"Information\". You rarely use them directly.  Responses with these status codes cannot have a body.\n\n- 200 is the default status code, which means everything was \"OK\".\n\n- Another example would be 201 , \"Created\". It is commonly used after creating a new record in the database.\n\n- A special case is 204 , \"No Content\".  This response is used when there is no content to return to the client, and so the response must not have a body.\n\n- An example is 404 , for a \"Not Found\" response.\n\n- For generic errors from the client, you can just use 400 .",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "100 - 199",
      "200",
      "201",
      "204",
      "404",
      "400"
    ],
    "section_links": [],
    "code_refs": [],
    "code_blocks": []
  },
  "tutorial/response-status-code::section-0003": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/response-status-code::section-0003",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/response-status-code::section-0001",
    "level": 2,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Shortcut to remember the names",
    "anchor_id": "shortcut-to-remember-the-names",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/response-status-code/#shortcut-to-remember-the-names",
    "section_text": "Let's see the previous example again:\n\n201 is the status code for \"Created\".\n\nBut you don't have to memorize what each of these codes mean.\n\nYou can use the convenience variables from fastapi.status .\n\nThey are just a convenience, they hold the same number, but that way you can use the editor's autocomplete to find them:",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "201",
      "fastapi.status"
    ],
